blurb":"US Minister to Russia under Polk; Congressman 1825-33","notable_category":["politics","law"],"primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ralph_I._Ingersoll","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia"},"birth":{"year":1789,"month":2,"day":8,"city":"New Haven","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1872,"month":8,"day":26,"city":"New Haven","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States","age":83},"residence":{},"burial":{"plot_notes":"Grove Street Cemetery, New Haven CT, 3 Maple Ave East"},"baptism":{},"cross_connections":[{"type":"in_law","related_id":"X02895","display_label":"was his father-in-law"}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"politics","header":"US Minister to Russia under President Polk","body":"Ralph Isaacs Ingersoll was appointed by Democratic President James K. Polk as the sixteenth United States Minister Plenipotentiary to the Russian Empire on August 8, 1846. He presented his credentials in Russia on May 30, 1847, and served until his resignation on July 1, 1848. The appointment was unsought and unexpected — he served his government 'faithfully and ably' before gladly returning to his New Haven law practice."},{"number":2,"category":"politics","header":"Four consecutive Congressional terms 1825-1833","body":"Ralph served four consecutive terms in the United States Congress representing Connecticut at-large from March 4, 1825 through March 3, 1833 — first elected as an Adams candidate, then reelected as Anti-Jacksonian. He served on the powerful Ways and Means committee for four years, holding the second-ranking position during his final term. He was not a candidate for renomination in 1832."},{"number":3,"category":"politics","header":"Declined US Senate seat from Governor Edwards, 1835","body":"In 1835 Governor Henry W. Edwards offered Ralph the United States Senate seat made vacant by the death of Senator Nathan Smith. He peremptorily declined — though the legislature would undoubtedly have elected him to the position. He similarly declined repeated gubernatorial nominations from his party across many years, departing from his settled purpose only once when Polk appointed him to Russia."},{"number":4,"category":"character","header":"Best public speaker his contemporaries ever knew","body":"One of Ralph's contemporaries with wide experience said of him 'he was the best public speaker I ever knew.' His voice was pleasant and almost musical, with unusual compass — distinct in its lowest tones. He was eminently persuasive before a jury or popular assembly, with a documented personal magnetism that allowed him to sway crowds, by turns humorous and pathetic, sarcastic when needed."},{"number":5,"category":"family","header":"Yale 1808, New Haven law, Grove Street burial","body":"Ralph graduated from Yale College in 1808 and read law for two years with Seth P. Staples before opening his New Haven practice. He married Margaret Catherine Eleanor Van den Heuvel in 1814 and they had seven children together — including future Governor of Connecticut Charles Roberts Ingersoll and US Congressman Colin Macrae Ingersoll. He died in New Haven August 26, 1872 at age eighty-three, buried at Grove Street Cemetery."}],"quotes":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST022","role":"student","notes":"Yale College class of 1808"},{"institution_id":"INST155","role":"student","notes":"Studied at Yale Law School after Yale College 1808"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"military_service":[],"education":[],"career":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Ralph Isaacs Ingersoll","first_name":"Ralph","last_name":"Ingersoll","middle_name":"Isaacs","married_names":[],"gender":"male"},"slug":"ralph-ingersoll-1789"},"HD5109":{"id":"HD5109","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,